  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "The logic for rendering the notes finds the first template ending in `NOTES.txt` (https://github.com/kubernetes/helm/blob/master/cmd/tiller/release_server.go#L673). Sometimes, it picks up the dependent chart's NOTES.txt, but it should always use the parent chart's NOTES.txt.\n\nFor example, when trying to install WordPress:\n\n```\n$ helm install stable/wordpress --namespace wp\nNAME: wiggly-seal\nLAST DEPLOYED: Tue Oct 18 16:11:34 2016\nNAMESPACE: wp\nSTATUS: DEPLOYED\n\nRESOURCES:\n==> extensions/Deployment\nNAME                    DESIRED   CURRENT   UP-TO-DATE   AVAILABLE   AGE\nwiggly-seal-wordpress   1         1         1            0           0s\nwiggly-seal-mariadb   1         1         1         0         0s\n\n==> v1/PersistentVolumeClaim\nNAME                  STATUS    VOLUME    CAPACITY   ACCESSMODES   AGE\nwiggly-seal-mariadb   Pending                                      1s\nwiggly-seal-wordpress-wordpress   Pending                                 0s\nwiggly-seal-wordpress-apache   Pending                                 0s\n\n==> v1/Service\nNAME                  CLUSTER-IP       EXTERNAL-IP   PORT(S)    AGE\nwiggly-seal-mariadb   10.103.242.118   <none>        3306/TCP   1s\nwiggly-seal-wordpress   10.103.251.176   <pending>   80/TCP,443/TCP   1s\n\n==> v1/Secret\nNAME                  TYPE      DATA      AGE\nwiggly-seal-mariadb   Opaque    2         0s\nwiggly-seal-wordpress   Opaque    2         0s\n\n\nNOTES:\nMariaDB can be accessed via port 3306 on the following DNS name from within your cluster:\nwiggly-seal-mariadb.wp.svc.cluster.local\n\nTo connect to your database run the following command:\n\n   kubectl run wiggly-seal-mariadb-client --rm --tty -i --image bitnami/mariadb --command -- mysql -h wiggly-seal-mariadb\n```\n",
